<h1>Estate Planning for Nurses 2026</h1>
<p style="font-size:1.15em;color:#444">Nurses spend careers helping families through the worst days, yet a surprising number haven't done the paperwork that would protect their own. Estate planning sounds like something for the wealthy or the elderly &mdash; it isn't. If you have any assets, a retirement account, a home, or (especially) children, you already have an estate, and either you decide what happens to it or your state's default rules decide for you. The good news: the core documents are straightforward, and getting them in place is one of the highest-leverage financial moves you can make.</p>
<div class="hero-note">
<strong>The short version:</strong> Five documents do the heavy lifting: a <strong>will</strong> (who gets what, and who raises your kids), <strong>beneficiary designations</strong> (which override your will on retirement accounts and life insurance), a <strong>durable power of attorney</strong> (who manages your money if you can't), an <strong>advance directive / healthcare proxy</strong> (your medical wishes and who speaks for you), and, for parents, a named <strong>guardian</strong>. The single most common mistake is out-of-date beneficiary forms &mdash; fix those first.</p>
</div>

<h2>The will: your instructions, and who raises your kids</h2>
<p>A will states who inherits your property and, critically for parents, names the guardian who would raise your minor children if you couldn't. Without a will, your state's intestacy laws decide who gets your assets &mdash; which may not match your wishes, especially in blended families or unmarried partnerships &mdash; and a court, not you, decides who raises your children. That guardian decision alone is reason enough for any nurse with kids to have a will. A will typically also names an executor, the person who carries out your instructions and settles the estate.</p>

<h2>The trap: beneficiary designations override your will</h2>
<p>This is the one that blindsides people. Retirement accounts (403(b), 401(k), IRAs), life insurance, and many bank/brokerage accounts pass by <em>beneficiary designation</em>, not by your will. Whoever is named on those forms gets the money &mdash; period &mdash; even if your will says something different. The classic disaster: a nurse names an ex-spouse as the 403(b) beneficiary early in their career, never updates it after divorce and remarriage, and the ex inherits the whole account regardless of the new will. Pull up every retirement account, life insurance policy, and HSA, and confirm the primary <em>and</em> contingent beneficiaries are current. This costs nothing and takes an afternoon.</p>
<div class="warning">
<strong>Check beneficiaries after every major life event.</strong> Marriage, divorce, a new child, a death in the family &mdash; each is a trigger to review every beneficiary form. Naming a minor child directly can also cause problems (a court may have to appoint a custodian for the money), so ask about a trust or a custodial arrangement if your children are young. Beneficiary forms are the fastest, cheapest fix in all of estate planning, and the most commonly neglected.</p>
</div>

<h2>Durable power of attorney: someone to manage the money</h2>
<p>A durable power of attorney (POA) names a trusted person to handle your financial affairs &mdash; pay bills, manage accounts, deal with your employer &mdash; if you become incapacitated. "Durable" means it stays in effect even after you're incapacitated (that's the whole point). Without one, your family may have to petition a court for guardianship or conservatorship to access your accounts, a slow and expensive process at the worst possible time. As a nurse, you've likely seen how quickly capacity can vanish; the POA is your insurance against that scenario.</p>

<h2>Advance directive and healthcare proxy: your voice in the room</h2>
<p>Here nurses have a real advantage &mdash; you know exactly what these decisions look like. An advance directive (living will) documents your wishes about life-sustaining treatment, and a healthcare proxy (or medical power of attorney) names the person who makes medical decisions for you if you can't speak for yourself. You've watched families agonize over choices a patient never wrote down; don't leave yours to guesswork. Complete both, discuss them frankly with the person you name, and make sure they're accessible &mdash; not locked in a drawer no one can reach.</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Document</th><th>What it does</th><th>Who needs it</th></tr>
<tr><td>Will</td><td>Distributes assets; names guardian for minor kids and an executor</td><td>Everyone, especially parents</td></tr>
<tr><td>Beneficiary designations</td><td>Passes retirement/life insurance directly &mdash; overrides the will</td><td>Anyone with these accounts</td></tr>
<tr><td>Durable POA (financial)</td><td>Lets someone manage your money if you're incapacitated</td><td>Everyone</td></tr>
<tr><td>Advance directive / healthcare proxy</td><td>Records medical wishes; names your medical decision-maker</td><td>Everyone</td></tr>
<tr><td>Guardian designation</td><td>Names who raises your minor children</td><td>Parents of minors</td></tr>
<tr><td>Trust (optional)</td><td>Avoids probate, controls timing of inheritances</td><td>Larger estates, young kids, privacy</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>Do you need a trust?</h2>
<p>Not everyone does. A revocable living trust can help you avoid probate (the public, sometimes slow court process of settling a will), control <em>when</em> and <em>how</em> heirs receive money (useful if your kids are young), and keep your affairs private. It's worth considering if you own real estate, have a larger estate, want to spare your family the probate process, or have minor children you don't want inheriting a lump sum at 18. For a nurse with modest assets and current beneficiary forms, a solid will plus the other core documents may be plenty. This is a good question for an estate attorney &mdash; but don't let "maybe I need a trust" become the reason you do nothing.</p>

<h2>Where to start without a big legal bill</h2>
<p>Update your beneficiary designations today &mdash; it's free and it's the most important single step. Then handle the core documents: many people use a reputable online estate-planning service for a straightforward will, POA, and advance directive, while those with real estate, blended families, or larger estates benefit from an estate attorney (often a flat fee for a full package). Check whether your employer offers a legal-services benefit; many hospital benefit menus include discounted estate planning. Store the documents somewhere your executor and proxy can actually find them, and tell those people they've been named &mdash; a document no one can locate helps no one.</p>
<div class="callout">
<strong>Bottom line:</strong> Estate planning isn't about being rich &mdash; it's about deciding, instead of letting the state decide. Fix your beneficiary designations first (they override your will), then get a will, a durable POA, and an advance directive in place; parents should name a guardian, and larger or more complex situations may warrant a trust. A weekend of paperwork spares your family months of stress.</p>
</div>
